##DESCRIPTION
##KEYWORDS('integrals', 'fundamental theorem of calculus')
##  Find a derivative of a given integral
##ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

#my ($a, $aaa, $answer);
$a= random(1, 5, 1);

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Use part I of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to
find the derivative of
\[ f(x) = \int_{-$a}^{x} \sqrt{t^3+\{$a**3\}} dt \]
$BR \( f'(x) \) = \{ans_rule( 20)\} $BR
[NOTE:  Enter a function as your answer.  Make sure that your
syntax is correct, i.e. remember to put all the necessary (, ), etc. ]
EOT

$aaa=$a**3;
$answer="sqrt(x^3+$aaa)" ;

&ANS(function_cmp($answer));

&SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));

$SOL $BR $BR

The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, part I, can be found on p.392 of your
textbook.  It says that if
\[ g(x) = \int_a^x f(t) dt \]
then the derivative of \(g(x)\) with respect to \(x\), written
\(\frac{d}{dx} g(x)\) or \(g'(x)\), is equal to \(f(x)\). $PAR

Applying this in this particular situation, we find
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\left(\int_{-$a}^x \left(\sqrt{t^3+$a^3}\right)dt\right)
= \sqrt{x^3+$a^3}
\]

EOT

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.

